0); Relationships (44, 69, 67)]. This represents the implementation of molecular oncology into clinical algorithms, enabling protocols to tailor innovative therapies that improve survival in defined patient subsets, and reflecting compliance with the latest treatment advances.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Comprehensive workup and surveillance steps reinforce protocol rigor\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Protocol nodes such as 'Additional workup' and 'Observe' codify required imaging, laboratory tests, and surveillance follow-up, ensuring quality control in patient management [Data: Entities (69, 70, 67); Relationships (178, 177, 179, 175)]. This structure minimizes missed diagnoses, supports early detection of recurrence, and formalizes surveillance pathways post-surgery or adjuvant therapy.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Protocols accommodate rare gastrointestinal malignancies and edge cases\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Entities referencing small bowel adenocarcinoma, appendiceal adenocarcinoma, and peritoneal/extrapleural mesothelioma reflect the thoroughness and interconnectedness of the protocol ecosystem, as these steps direct treatment for less common, but clinically significant, GI cancers [Data: Entities (73, 74, 75); Relationships (169, 170, 171)]. Their inclusion requires clinicians to consult the appropriate guidelines for these subtypes, promoting best practices across GI oncology.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Adjuvant therapy and surveillance link to multiple protocol steps\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The entity 'ADJUVANT (up to 6 mo)'—encompassing FOLFOX, CAPEOX, Capecitabine, or fluorouracil/leucovorin—feeds directly into surveillance protocols, with downstream monitoring encoded as 'Surveillance → COL-8' [Data: Entities (87); Relationships (232, 231)]. Sequential nodes ensure both adjuvant intent and safety nets post-treatment, reflecting a closed-loop system that aims to optimize disease-free and overall survival.\"\n    }